{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"720f00bb-554f-4640-b027-17183e5156fb","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically captures crash reports — no `createdump` needed.\n\n**Crash reports (`.ips` files):**\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n```\nLook for a file matching your process name with a recent timestamp. You can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them.\n\n**Core dumps:**\nmacOS can also generate core dumps, but they're off by default. To enable:\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\nThen reproduce the crash. Core files appear in `/cores/`.\n\n**Tip:** The `.ips` crash report is usually the easiest starting point — it includes the backtrace, signal info, and loaded libraries. If you need to symbolicate the .NET runtime frames in that `.ips` file, let me know.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d1726467-422a-4003-9b54-11437da59e5c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, specifically without `createdump`. This is a knowledge question — I don't need to search a codebase. Let me answer directly.\n\nOn macOS, when an app crashes, the system automatically generates a crash report (`.ips` file). These are stored in:\n\n- `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for user-space crashes)\n- `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for system-wide crashes)\n\nFor NativeAOT apps, `createdump` is not included by default (it's a CoreCLR tool). But macOS itself captures crash reports via ReportCrash.\n\n\nI can also enable core dumps directly with `ulimit -c unlimited`, which will write them to `/cores/` for more detailed debugging if needed.","outputTokens":427,"requestId":"600D:15FDF:DCF3C4:1003386:69EACAA1"},"id":"b74245b5-10f7-4acc-99b5-168cde206306","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:43:07.945Z","parentId":"e89e8182-fa4b-4517-a541-80fce747513b"}
